JOHANNESBURG, October 24 – A 54-year-old police officer stationed at Marianhill has been shot and killed in KwaZulu-Natal, KwaNdengezi, police said on Wednesday. Spokesperson Brigadier Vishnu Naidoo said warrant officer Bhekisigcino Zethembe Khwela was in the company of his son and a friend chatting outside his house in KwaNdengezi after 7 pm on Tuesday. “Two gunmen, who were on foot, fired several shots at them, his son was wounded and the friend managed to escape,” said Naidoo. In a separate incident on Tuesday Captain Lumkile Wiseman Tyibilika was killed in New Brighton in the Eastern Cape. The National Commissioner of Police, General Khehla John Sitole has condemned the continuous killing of police officers. “The killing of our two colleagues yesterday is a reflection of what police must endure on a daily basis. “I have instructed the Provincial Commissioners of both the Eastern Cape and KwaZulu-Natal to mobilise maximum resources to track down those responsible and bring them to book”, added Sitole. Sitole said the motives for both incidents were not known at this stage. In both incidents, the 72-hour Activation Plan, which mobilises critical resources, was being implemented. – African News Agency (ANA)